<statement><div><p>Classify each of the following data collection activities as either <alert>Primary Data</alert> or <alert>Secondary Data</alert>:</p>

<div class="card mb-3">
  <div class="card-body">
    <p><alert>(a)</alert> You interview 20 students to ask them about their favorite lunch meal.</p>
    [ Primary Data | Secondary Data ] 
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card mb-3">
  <div class="card-body">
    <p><alert>(b)</alert> You search the internet for the current exchange rate of the Dollar.</p>
    [ Secondary Data | Primary Data ] 
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card mb-3">
  <div class="card-body">
    <p><alert>(c)</alert> You hand out a questionnaire to your neighbors about water usage.</p>
    [ Secondary Data | Primary Data ] 
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card mb-3">
  <div class="card-body">
    <p><alert>(d)</alert> You use a graph from a textbook to analyze rainfall patterns from 1990.</p>
    [ Primary Data | Secondary Data ] 
  </div>
</div></div></statement>
<solution><div><h3>Worked solution</h3>
<ul>
    <li><alert>Primary Data:</alert> This is data that you collect <em>yourself</em> for a specific purpose. It is "fresh" and original. (Examples: Counting cars, interviewing people, measuring height).</li>
    <li><alert>Secondary Data:</alert> This is data that <em>someone else</em> has already collected. You are just using it. (Examples: Census reports, newspaper articles, textbooks, internet searches).</li>
</ul></div></solution>
<answer><p>Primary Data</p></answer>
<answer><p>Secondary Data</p></answer>
<answer><p>Primary Data</p></answer>
<answer><p>Secondary Data</p></answer>
